594 void MachineFunction::print(raw_ostream &OS, const SlotIndexes *Indexes) const { 0
595 OS << "# Machine code for function " << getName() << ": "; 0
596 getProperties().print(OS); 0
597 OS << '\n'; 0
598 ----
599 // Print Frame Information ----
600 FrameInfo->print(*this, OS); 0
601 ----
602 // Print JumpTable Information ----
603 if (JumpTableInfo) 0
604 JumpTableInfo->print(OS); 0
605 ----
606 // Print Constant Pool ----
607 ConstantPool->print(OS); 0
608 ----
609 const TargetRegisterInfo *TRI = getSubtarget().getRegisterInfo(); 0
610 ----
611 if (RegInfo && !RegInfo->livein_empty()) { 0
612 OS << "Function Live Ins: "; 0
613 for (MachineRegisterInfo::livein_iterator 0
614 I = RegInfo->livein_begin(), E = RegInfo->livein_end(); I != E; ++I) { 0
615 OS << printReg(I->first, TRI); 0
616 if (I->second) 0
617 OS << " in " << printReg(I->second, TRI); 0
618 if (std::next(I) != E) 0
619 OS << ", "; 0
620 } ----
621 OS << '\n'; 0
622 } ----
623 ----
624 ModuleSlotTracker MST(getFunction().getParent()); 0
625 MST.incorporateFunction(getFunction()); 0
626 for (const auto &BB : *this) { 0
627 OS << '\n'; 0
628 // If we print the whole function, print it at its most verbose level. ----
629 BB.print(OS, MST, Indexes, /*IsStandalone=*/true); 0
630 } ----
631 ----
632 OS << "\n# End machine code for function " << getName() << ".\n\n"; 0
633 } 0

637 return getMMI().hasDebugInfo() || 0
638 getTarget().Options.ForceDwarfFrameSection || 0
639 F.needsUnwindTableEntry(); 0
640 } ----

653 const MachineFunction *Graph) { ----
654 std::string OutStr; 0
655 { ----
656 raw_string_ostream OSS(OutStr); 0
657 ----
658 if (isSimple()) { 0
659 OSS << printMBBReference(*Node); 0
660 if (const BasicBlock *BB = Node->getBasicBlock()) 0
661 OSS << ": " << BB->getName(); 0
662 } else ----
663 Node->print(OSS); 0
664 } 0
665 ----
666 if (OutStr[0] == '\n') OutStr.erase(OutStr.begin()); 0
667 ----
668 // Process string output to make it nicer... ----
669 for (unsigned i = 0; i != OutStr.length(); ++i) 0
670 if (OutStr[i] == '\n') { // Left justify 0
671 OutStr[i] = '\\'; 0
672 OutStr.insert(OutStr.begin()+i+1, 'l'); 0
673 } ----
674 return OutStr; 0
675 } ----

700 /// Add the specified physical register as a live-in value and ----
701 /// create a corresponding virtual register for it. ----
702 Register MachineFunction::addLiveIn(MCRegister PReg, 0
703 const TargetRegisterClass *RC) { ----
704 MachineRegisterInfo &MRI = getRegInfo(); 0
705 Register VReg = MRI.getLiveInVirtReg(PReg); 0
706 if (VReg) { 0
707 const TargetRegisterClass *VRegRC = MRI.getRegClass(VReg); 0
708 (void)VRegRC; ----
709 // A physical register can be added several times. ----
710 // Between two calls, the register class of the related virtual register ----
711 // may have been constrained to match some operation constraints. ----
712 // In that case, check that the current register class includes the ----
713 // physical register and is a sub class of the specified RC. ----
714 assert((VRegRC == RC || (VRegRC->contains(PReg) && 0
715 RC->hasSubClassEq(VRegRC))) && ----
716 "Register class mismatch!"); ----
717 return VReg; 0
718 } ----
719 VReg = MRI.createVirtualRegister(RC); 0
720 MRI.addLiveIn(PReg, VReg); 0
721 return VReg; 0
722 } ----

726 /// normal 'L' label is returned. ----
727 MCSymbol *MachineFunction::getJTISymbol(unsigned JTI, MCContext &Ctx, 0
728 bool isLinkerPrivate) const { ----

730 assert(JumpTableInfo && "No jump tables"); 0
731 assert(JTI < JumpTableInfo->getJumpTables().size() && "Invalid JTI!"); 0
732 ----
733 StringRef Prefix = isLinkerPrivate ? DL.getLinkerPrivateGlobalPrefix() 0
734 : DL.getPrivateGlobalPrefix(); 0
735 SmallString<60> Name; 0
736 raw_svector_ostream(Name) 0
737 << Prefix << "JTI" << getFunctionNumber() << '_' << JTI; 0
738 return Ctx.getOrCreateSymbol(Name); 0
739 } 0

751 LandingPadInfo & ----
752 MachineFunction::getOrCreateLandingPadInfo(MachineBasicBlock *LandingPad) { 0
753 unsigned N = LandingPads.size(); 0
754 for (unsigned i = 0; i < N; ++i) { 0
755 LandingPadInfo &LP = LandingPads[i]; 0
756 if (LP.LandingPadBlock == LandingPad) 0
757 return LP; 0
758 } ----
759 ----
760 LandingPads.push_back(LandingPadInfo(LandingPad)); 0
761 return LandingPads[N]; 0

764 void MachineFunction::addInvoke(MachineBasicBlock *LandingPad, 0
765 MCSymbol *BeginLabel, MCSymbol *EndLabel) { ----

767 LP.BeginLabels.push_back(BeginLabel); 0
768 LP.EndLabels.push_back(EndLabel); 0
769 } 0
770 ----
771 MCSymbol *MachineFunction::addLandingPad(MachineBasicBlock *LandingPad) { 0
772 MCSymbol *LandingPadLabel = Ctx.createTempSymbol(); 0
773 LandingPadInfo &LP = getOrCreateLandingPadInfo(LandingPad); 0
774 LP.LandingPadLabel = LandingPadLabel; 0
775 ----
776 const Instruction *FirstI = LandingPad->getBasicBlock()->getFirstNonPHI(); 0
777 if (const auto *LPI = dyn_cast(FirstI)) { 0
778 // If there's no typeid list specified, then "cleanup" is implicit. ----
779 // Otherwise, id 0 is reserved for the cleanup action. ----
780 if (LPI->isCleanup() && LPI->getNumClauses() != 0) 0
781 LP.TypeIds.push_back(0); 0
782 ----
783 // FIXME: New EH - Add the clauses in reverse order. This isn't 100% ----
784 // correct, but we need to do it this way because of how the DWARF EH ----
785 // emitter processes the clauses. ----
786 for (unsigned I = LPI->getNumClauses(); I != 0; --I) { 0
787 Value *Val = LPI->getClause(I - 1); 0
788 if (LPI->isCatch(I - 1)) { 0
789 LP.TypeIds.push_back( 0
790 getTypeIDFor(dyn_cast(Val->stripPointerCasts()))); 0
791 } else { ----
792 // Add filters in a list. ----
793 auto *CVal = cast(Val); 0
794 SmallVector FilterList; 0
795 for (const Use &U : CVal->operands()) 0
796 FilterList.push_back( 0
797 getTypeIDFor(cast(U->stripPointerCasts()))); ----
798 ----
799 LP.TypeIds.push_back(getFilterIDFor(FilterList)); 0
800 } 0
801 } ----
802 ----
803 } else if (const auto *CPI = dyn_cast(FirstI)) { 0
804 for (unsigned I = CPI->arg_size(); I != 0; --I) { 0
805 auto *TypeInfo = ----
806 dyn_cast(CPI->getArgOperand(I - 1)->stripPointerCasts()); 0
807 LP.TypeIds.push_back(getTypeIDFor(TypeInfo)); 0
808 } ----
809 ----
810 } else { ----
811 assert(isa(FirstI) && "Invalid landingpad!"); 0
812 } ----
813 ----
814 return LandingPadLabel; 0
815 } ----

818 ArrayRef Sites) { ----
819 LPadToCallSiteMap[Sym].append(Sites.begin(), Sites.end()); 0
820 } 0
821 ----
822 unsigned MachineFunction::getTypeIDFor(const GlobalValue *TI) { 0
823 for (unsigned i = 0, N = TypeInfos.size(); i != N; ++i) 0
824 if (TypeInfos[i] == TI) return i + 1; 0
825 ----
826 TypeInfos.push_back(TI); 0
827 return TypeInfos.size(); 0
828 } ----
829 ----
830 int MachineFunction::getFilterIDFor(ArrayRef TyIds) { 0
831 // If the new filter coincides with the tail of an existing filter, then ----
832 // re-use the existing filter. Folding filters more than this requires ----
833 // re-ordering filters and/or their elements - probably not worth it. ----
834 for (unsigned i : FilterEnds) { 0
835 unsigned j = TyIds.size(); 0
836 ----
837 while (i && j) 0
838 if (FilterIds[--i] != TyIds[--j]) 0
839 goto try_next; 0
840 ----
841 if (!j) 0
842 // The new filter coincides with range [i, end) of the existing filter. ----
843 return -(1 + i); 0
844 ----
845 try_next:; 0
846 } ----
847 ----
848 // Add the new filter. ----
849 int FilterID = -(1 + FilterIds.size()); 0
850 FilterIds.reserve(FilterIds.size() + TyIds.size() + 1); 0
851 llvm::append_range(FilterIds, TyIds); 0
852 FilterEnds.push_back(FilterIds.size()); 0
853 FilterIds.push_back(0); // terminator 0
854 return FilterID; 0
855 } ----

857 MachineFunction::CallSiteInfoMap::iterator ----
858 MachineFunction::getCallSiteInfo(const MachineInstr *MI) { 0
859 assert(MI->isCandidateForCallSiteEntry() && 0
860 "Call site info refers only to call (MI) candidates"); ----
861 ----
862 if (!Target.Options.EmitCallSiteInfo) 0
863 return CallSitesInfo.end(); 0
864 return CallSitesInfo.find(MI); 0
865 } ----
866 ----
867 /// Return the call machine instruction or find a call within bundle. ----
868 static const MachineInstr *getCallInstr(const MachineInstr *MI) { 0
869 if (!MI->isBundle()) 0
870 return MI; 0
871 ----
872 for (const auto &BMI : make_range(getBundleStart(MI->getIterator()), 0
873 getBundleEnd(MI->getIterator()))) 0
874 if (BMI.isCandidateForCallSiteEntry()) 0
875 return &BMI; 0
876 ----
877 llvm_unreachable("Unexpected bundle without a call site candidate"); 0
878 } ----
879 ----
880 void MachineFunction::eraseCallSiteInfo(const MachineInstr *MI) { 0
881 assert(MI->shouldUpdateCallSiteInfo() && 0
882 "Call site info refers only to call (MI) candidates or " ----
883 "candidates inside bundles"); ----
884 ----
885 const MachineInstr *CallMI = getCallInstr(MI); 0
886 CallSiteInfoMap::iterator CSIt = getCallSiteInfo(CallMI); 0
887 if (CSIt == CallSitesInfo.end()) 0
888 return; 0
889 CallSitesInfo.erase(CSIt); 0
890 } ----
891 ----
892 void MachineFunction::copyCallSiteInfo(const MachineInstr *Old, 0
893 const MachineInstr *New) { ----
894 assert(Old->shouldUpdateCallSiteInfo() && 0
895 "Call site info refers only to call (MI) candidates or " ----
896 "candidates inside bundles"); ----
897 ----
898 if (!New->isCandidateForCallSiteEntry()) 0
899 return eraseCallSiteInfo(Old); 0
900 ----
901 const MachineInstr *OldCallMI = getCallInstr(Old); 0
902 CallSiteInfoMap::iterator CSIt = getCallSiteInfo(OldCallMI); 0
903 if (CSIt == CallSitesInfo.end()) 0
904 return; 0
905 ----
906 CallSiteInfo CSInfo = CSIt->second; 0
907 CallSitesInfo[New] = CSInfo; 0
908 } 0
909 ----
910 void MachineFunction::moveCallSiteInfo(const MachineInstr *Old, 0
911 const MachineInstr *New) { ----
912 assert(Old->shouldUpdateCallSiteInfo() && 0
913 "Call site info refers only to call (MI) candidates or " ----
914 "candidates inside bundles"); ----
915 ----
916 if (!New->isCandidateForCallSiteEntry()) 0
917 return eraseCallSiteInfo(Old); 0
918 ----
919 const MachineInstr *OldCallMI = getCallInstr(Old); 0
920 CallSiteInfoMap::iterator CSIt = getCallSiteInfo(OldCallMI); 0
921 if (CSIt == CallSitesInfo.end()) 0
922 return; 0
923 ----
924 CallSiteInfo CSInfo = std::move(CSIt->second); 0
925 CallSitesInfo.erase(CSIt); 0
926 CallSitesInfo[New] = CSInfo; 0
927 } 0

932 ----
933 void MachineFunction::makeDebugValueSubstitution(DebugInstrOperandPair A, 0
934 DebugInstrOperandPair B, ----
935 unsigned Subreg) { ----
936 // Catch any accidental self-loops. ----
937 assert(A.first != B.first); 0
938 // Don't allow any substitutions _from_ the memory operand number. ----
939 assert(A.second != DebugOperandMemNumber); 0
940 ----
941 DebugValueSubstitutions.push_back({A, B, Subreg}); 0
942 } 0
943 ----
944 void MachineFunction::substituteDebugValuesForInst(const MachineInstr &Old, 0
945 MachineInstr &New, ----
946 unsigned MaxOperand) { ----
947 // If the Old instruction wasn't tracked at all, there is no work to do. ----
948 unsigned OldInstrNum = Old.peekDebugInstrNum(); 0
949 if (!OldInstrNum) 0
950 return; 0
951 ----
952 // Iterate over all operands looking for defs to create substitutions for. ----
953 // Avoid creating new instr numbers unless we create a new substitution. ----
954 // While this has no functional effect, it risks confusing someone reading ----
955 // MIR output. ----
956 // Examine all the operands, or the first N specified by the caller. ----
957 MaxOperand = std::min(MaxOperand, Old.getNumOperands()); 0
958 for (unsigned int I = 0; I < MaxOperand; ++I) { 0
959 const auto &OldMO = Old.getOperand(I); 0
960 auto &NewMO = New.getOperand(I); 0
961 (void)NewMO; ----
962 ----
963 if (!OldMO.isReg() || !OldMO.isDef()) 0
964 continue; 0
965 assert(NewMO.isDef()); 0
966 ----
967 unsigned NewInstrNum = New.getDebugInstrNum(); 0
968 makeDebugValueSubstitution(std::make_pair(OldInstrNum, I), 0
969 std::make_pair(NewInstrNum, I)); ----
970 } ----
971 } ----
972 ----
973 auto MachineFunction::salvageCopySSA( 0
974 MachineInstr &MI, DenseMap &DbgPHICache) ----
975 -> DebugInstrOperandPair { ----
976 const TargetInstrInfo &TII = *getSubtarget().getInstrInfo(); 0
977 ----
978 // Check whether this copy-like instruction has already been salvaged into ----
979 // an operand pair. ----
980 Register Dest; 0
981 if (auto CopyDstSrc = TII.isCopyInstr(MI)) { 0
982 Dest = CopyDstSrc->Destination->getReg(); 0
983 } else { ----
984 assert(MI.isSubregToReg()); 0
985 Dest = MI.getOperand(0).getReg(); 0
986 } ----
987 ----
988 auto CacheIt = DbgPHICache.find(Dest); 0
989 if (CacheIt != DbgPHICache.end()) 0
990 return CacheIt->second; 0
991 ----
992 // Calculate the instruction number to use, or install a DBG_PHI. ----
993 auto OperandPair = salvageCopySSAImpl(MI); 0
994 DbgPHICache.insert({Dest, OperandPair}); 0
995 return OperandPair; 0
996 } ----
997 ----
998 auto MachineFunction::salvageCopySSAImpl(MachineInstr &MI) 0
999 -> DebugInstrOperandPair { ----
1000 MachineRegisterInfo &MRI = getRegInfo(); 0
1001 const TargetRegisterInfo &TRI = *MRI.getTargetRegisterInfo(); 0
1002 const TargetInstrInfo &TII = *getSubtarget().getInstrInfo(); 0
1003 ----
1004 // Chase the value read by a copy-like instruction back to the instruction ----
1005 // that ultimately _defines_ that value. This may pass: ----
1006 // * Through multiple intermediate copies, including subregister moves / ----
1007 // copies, ----
1008 // * Copies from physical registers that must then be traced back to the ----
1009 // defining instruction, ----
1010 // * Or, physical registers may be live-in to (only) the entry block, which ----
1011 // requires a DBG_PHI to be created. ----
1012 // We can pursue this problem in that order: trace back through copies, ----
1013 // optionally through a physical register, to a defining instruction. We ----
1014 // should never move from physreg to vreg. As we're still in SSA form, no need ----
1015 // to worry about partial definitions of registers. ----
1016 ----
1017 // Helper lambda to interpret a copy-like instruction. Takes instruction, ----
1018 // returns the register read and any subregister identifying which part is ----
1019 // read. ----
1020 auto GetRegAndSubreg = ----
1021 [&](const MachineInstr &Cpy) -> std::pair { 0
1022 Register NewReg, OldReg; 0
1023 unsigned SubReg; ----
1024 if (Cpy.isCopy()) { 0
1025 OldReg = Cpy.getOperand(0).getReg(); 0
1026 NewReg = Cpy.getOperand(1).getReg(); 0
1027 SubReg = Cpy.getOperand(1).getSubReg(); 0
1028 } else if (Cpy.isSubregToReg()) { 0
1029 OldReg = Cpy.getOperand(0).getReg(); 0
1030 NewReg = Cpy.getOperand(2).getReg(); 0
1031 SubReg = Cpy.getOperand(3).getImm(); 0
1032 } else { ----
1033 auto CopyDetails = *TII.isCopyInstr(Cpy); 0
1034 const MachineOperand &Src = *CopyDetails.Source; 0
1035 const MachineOperand &Dest = *CopyDetails.Destination; 0
1036 OldReg = Dest.getReg(); 0
1037 NewReg = Src.getReg(); 0
1038 SubReg = Src.getSubReg(); 0
1039 } ----
1040 ----
1041 return {NewReg, SubReg}; 0
1042 }; 0
1043 ----
1044 // First seek either the defining instruction, or a copy from a physreg. ----
1045 // During search, the current state is the current copy instruction, and which ----
1046 // register we've read. Accumulate qualifying subregisters into SubregsSeen; ----
1047 // deal with those later. ----
1048 auto State = GetRegAndSubreg(MI); 0
1049 auto CurInst = MI.getIterator(); 0
1050 SmallVector SubregsSeen; 0
1051 while (true) { ----
1052 // If we've found a copy from a physreg, first portion of search is over. ----
1053 if (!State.first.isVirtual()) 0
1054 break; 0
1055 ----
1056 // Record any subregister qualifier. ----
1057 if (State.second) 0
1058 SubregsSeen.push_back(State.second); 0
1059 ----
1060 assert(MRI.hasOneDef(State.first)); 0
1061 MachineInstr &Inst = *MRI.def_begin(State.first)->getParent(); 0
1062 CurInst = Inst.getIterator(); 0
1063 ----
1064 // Any non-copy instruction is the defining instruction we're seeking. ----
1065 if (!Inst.isCopyLike() && !TII.isCopyInstr(Inst)) 0
1066 break; 0
1067 State = GetRegAndSubreg(Inst); 0
1068 }; 0
1069 ----
1070 // Helper lambda to apply additional subregister substitutions to a known ----
1071 // instruction/operand pair. Adds new (fake) substitutions so that we can ----
1072 // record the subregister. FIXME: this isn't very space efficient if multiple ----
1073 // values are tracked back through the same copies; cache something later. ----
1074 auto ApplySubregisters = ----
1075 [&](DebugInstrOperandPair P) -> DebugInstrOperandPair { 0
1076 for (unsigned Subreg : reverse(SubregsSeen)) { 0
1077 // Fetch a new instruction number, not attached to an actual instruction. ----
1078 unsigned NewInstrNumber = getNewDebugInstrNum(); 0
1079 // Add a substitution from the "new" number to the known one, with a ----
1080 // qualifying subreg. ----
1081 makeDebugValueSubstitution({NewInstrNumber, 0}, P, Subreg); 0
1082 // Return the new number; to find the underlying value, consumers need to ----
1083 // deal with the qualifying subreg. ----
1084 P = {NewInstrNumber, 0}; 0
1085 } ----
1086 return P; 0
1087 }; 0
1088 ----
1089 // If we managed to find the defining instruction after COPYs, return an ----
1090 // instruction / operand pair after adding subregister qualifiers. ----
1091 if (State.first.isVirtual()) { 0
1092 // Virtual register def -- we can just look up where this happens. ----
1093 MachineInstr *Inst = MRI.def_begin(State.first)->getParent(); 0
1094 for (auto &MO : Inst->all_defs()) { 0
1095 if (MO.getReg() != State.first) 0
1096 continue; 0
1097 return ApplySubregisters({Inst->getDebugInstrNum(), MO.getOperandNo()}); 0
1098 } ----
1099 ----
1100 llvm_unreachable("Vreg def with no corresponding operand?"); 0
1101 } ----
1102 ----
1103 // Our search ended in a copy from a physreg: walk back up the function ----
1104 // looking for whatever defines the physreg. ----
1105 assert(CurInst->isCopyLike() || TII.isCopyInstr(*CurInst)); 0
1106 State = GetRegAndSubreg(*CurInst); 0
1107 Register RegToSeek = State.first; 0
1108 ----
1109 auto RMII = CurInst->getReverseIterator(); 0
1110 auto PrevInstrs = make_range(RMII, CurInst->getParent()->instr_rend()); 0
1111 for (auto &ToExamine : PrevInstrs) { 0
1112 for (auto &MO : ToExamine.all_defs()) { 0
1113 // Test for operand that defines something aliasing RegToSeek. ----
1114 if (!TRI.regsOverlap(RegToSeek, MO.getReg())) 0
1115 continue; 0
1116 ----
1117 return ApplySubregisters( 0
1118 {ToExamine.getDebugInstrNum(), MO.getOperandNo()}); 0
1119 } ----
1120 } ----
1121 ----
1122 MachineBasicBlock &InsertBB = *CurInst->getParent(); 0
1123 ----
1124 // We reached the start of the block before finding a defining instruction. ----
1125 // There are numerous scenarios where this can happen: ----
1126 // * Constant physical registers, ----
1127 // * Several intrinsics that allow LLVM-IR to read arbitary registers, ----
1128 // * Arguments in the entry block, ----
1129 // * Exception handling landing pads. ----
1130 // Validating all of them is too difficult, so just insert a DBG_PHI reading ----
1131 // the variable value at this position, rather than checking it makes sense. ----
1132 ----
1133 // Create DBG_PHI for specified physreg. ----
1134 auto Builder = BuildMI(InsertBB, InsertBB.getFirstNonPHI(), DebugLoc(), 0
1135 TII.get(TargetOpcode::DBG_PHI)); ----
1136 Builder.addReg(State.first); 0
1137 unsigned NewNum = getNewDebugInstrNum(); 0
1138 Builder.addImm(NewNum); 0
1139 return ApplySubregisters({NewNum, 0u}); 0
1140 } 0
1141 ----
1142 void MachineFunction::finalizeDebugInstrRefs() { 0
1143 auto *TII = getSubtarget().getInstrInfo(); 0
1144 ----
1145 auto MakeUndefDbgValue = [&](MachineInstr &MI) { 0
1146 const MCInstrDesc &RefII = TII->get(TargetOpcode::DBG_VALUE_LIST); 0
1147 MI.setDesc(RefII); 0
1148 MI.setDebugValueUndef(); 0
1149 }; 0
1150 ----
1151 DenseMap ArgDbgPHIs; 0
1152 for (auto &MBB : *this) { 0
1153 for (auto &MI : MBB) { 0
1154 if (!MI.isDebugRef()) 0
1155 continue; 0
1156 ----
1157 bool IsValidRef = true; 0
1158 ----
1159 for (MachineOperand &MO : MI.debug_operands()) { 0
1160 if (!MO.isReg()) 0
1161 continue; 0
1162 ----
1163 Register Reg = MO.getReg(); 0
1164 ----
1165 // Some vregs can be deleted as redundant in the meantime. Mark those ----
1166 // as DBG_VALUE $noreg. Additionally, some normal instructions are ----
1167 // quickly deleted, leaving dangling references to vregs with no def. ----
1168 if (Reg == 0 || !RegInfo->hasOneDef(Reg)) { 0
1169 IsValidRef = false; 0
1170 break; 0
1171 } ----
1172 ----
1173 assert(Reg.isVirtual()); 0
1174 MachineInstr &DefMI = *RegInfo->def_instr_begin(Reg); 0
1175 ----
1176 // If we've found a copy-like instruction, follow it back to the ----
1177 // instruction that defines the source value, see salvageCopySSA docs ----
1178 // for why this is important. ----
1179 if (DefMI.isCopyLike() || TII->isCopyInstr(DefMI)) { 0
1180 auto Result = salvageCopySSA(DefMI, ArgDbgPHIs); 0
1181 MO.ChangeToDbgInstrRef(Result.first, Result.second); 0
1182 } else { ----
1183 // Otherwise, identify the operand number that the VReg refers to. ----
1184 unsigned OperandIdx = 0; 0
1185 for (const auto &DefMO : DefMI.operands()) { 0
1186 if (DefMO.isReg() && DefMO.isDef() && DefMO.getReg() == Reg) 0
1187 break; 0
1188 ++OperandIdx; 0
1189 } ----
1190 assert(OperandIdx < DefMI.getNumOperands()); 0
1191 ----
1192 // Morph this instr ref to point at the given instruction and operand. ----
1193 unsigned ID = DefMI.getDebugInstrNum(); 0
1194 MO.ChangeToDbgInstrRef(ID, OperandIdx); 0
1195 } ----
1196 } ----
1197 ----
1198 if (!IsValidRef) 0
1199 MakeUndefDbgValue(MI); 0
1200 } ----
1201 } ----
1202 } 0

1212 // Don't use instr-ref if this function is marked optnone. ----
1213 if (F.hasFnAttribute(Attribute::OptimizeNone)) 2 ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips_dbg.ll ../DebugInfoTest/example_mips.ll

1239 /// Return the size of each entry in the jump table. ----
1240 unsigned MachineJumpTableInfo::getEntrySize(const DataLayout &TD) const { 0
1241 // The size of a jump table entry is 4 bytes unless the entry is just the ----
1242 // address of a block, in which case it is the pointer size. ----
1243 switch (getEntryKind()) { 0
1244 case MachineJumpTableInfo::EK_BlockAddress: 0
1245 return TD.getPointerSize(); 0
1246 case MachineJumpTableInfo::EK_GPRel64BlockAddress: 0
1247 return 8; 0
1248 case MachineJumpTableInfo::EK_GPRel32BlockAddress: 0
1249 case MachineJumpTableInfo::EK_LabelDifference32: ----
1250 case MachineJumpTableInfo::EK_Custom32: ----
1251 return 4; 0
1252 case MachineJumpTableInfo::EK_Inline: 0
1253 return 0; 0
1254 } ----
1255 llvm_unreachable("Unknown jump table encoding!"); 0
1256 } ----
1257 ----
1258 /// Return the alignment of each entry in the jump table. ----
1259 unsigned MachineJumpTableInfo::getEntryAlignment(const DataLayout &TD) const { 0
1260 // The alignment of a jump table entry is the alignment of int32 unless the ----
1261 // entry is just the address of a block, in which case it is the pointer ----
1262 // alignment. ----
1263 switch (getEntryKind()) { 0
1264 case MachineJumpTableInfo::EK_BlockAddress: 0
1265 return TD.getPointerABIAlignment(0).value(); 0
1266 case MachineJumpTableInfo::EK_GPRel64BlockAddress: 0
1267 return TD.getABIIntegerTypeAlignment(64).value(); 0
1268 case MachineJumpTableInfo::EK_GPRel32BlockAddress: 0
1269 case MachineJumpTableInfo::EK_LabelDifference32: ----
1270 case MachineJumpTableInfo::EK_Custom32: ----
1271 return TD.getABIIntegerTypeAlignment(32).value(); 0
1272 case MachineJumpTableInfo::EK_Inline: 0
1273 return 1; 0
1274 } ----
1275 llvm_unreachable("Unknown jump table encoding!"); 0
1276 } ----

1403 /// Test whether the given two constants can be allocated the same constant pool ----
1404 /// entry referenced by \param A. ----
1405 static bool CanShareConstantPoolEntry(const Constant *A, const Constant *B, 0
1406 const DataLayout &DL) { ----
1407 // Handle the trivial case quickly. ----
1408 if (A == B) return true; 0
1409 ----
1410 // If they have the same type but weren't the same constant, quickly ----
1411 // reject them. ----
1412 if (A->getType() == B->getType()) return false; 0
1413 ----
1414 // We can't handle structs or arrays. ----
1415 if (isa(A->getType()) || isa(A->getType()) || 0
1416 isa(B->getType()) || isa(B->getType())) 0
1417 return false; 0
1418 ----
1419 // For now, only support constants with the same size. ----
1420 uint64_t StoreSize = DL.getTypeStoreSize(A->getType()); 0
1421 if (StoreSize != DL.getTypeStoreSize(B->getType()) || StoreSize > 128) 0
1422 return false; 0
1423 ----
1424 bool ContainsUndefOrPoisonA = A->containsUndefOrPoisonElement(); 0
1425 ----
1426 Type *IntTy = IntegerType::get(A->getContext(), StoreSize*8); 0
1427 ----
1428 // Try constant folding a bitcast of both instructions to an integer. If we ----
1429 // get two identical ConstantInt's, then we are good to share them. We use ----
1430 // the constant folding APIs to do this so that we get the benefit of ----
1431 // DataLayout. ----
1432 if (isa(A->getType())) 0
1433 A = ConstantFoldCastOperand(Instruction::PtrToInt, 0
1434 const_cast(A), IntTy, DL); ----
1435 else if (A->getType() != IntTy) 0
1436 A = ConstantFoldCastOperand(Instruction::BitCast, const_cast(A), 0
1437 IntTy, DL); ----
1438 if (isa(B->getType())) 0
1439 B = ConstantFoldCastOperand(Instruction::PtrToInt, 0
1440 const_cast(B), IntTy, DL); ----
1441 else if (B->getType() != IntTy) 0
1442 B = ConstantFoldCastOperand(Instruction::BitCast, const_cast(B), 0
1443 IntTy, DL); ----
1444 ----
1445 if (A != B) 0
1446 return false; 0
1447 ----
1448 // Constants only safely match if A doesn't contain undef/poison. ----
1449 // As we'll be reusing A, it doesn't matter if B contain undef/poison. ----
1450 // TODO: Handle cases where A and B have the same undef/poison elements. ----
1451 // TODO: Merge A and B with mismatching undef/poison elements. ----
1452 return !ContainsUndefOrPoisonA; 0
1453 } ----
1454 ----
1455 /// Create a new entry in the constant pool or return an existing one. ----
1456 /// User must specify the log2 of the minimum required alignment for the object. ----
1457 unsigned MachineConstantPool::getConstantPoolIndex(const Constant *C, 0
1458 Align Alignment) { ----
1459 if (Alignment > PoolAlignment) PoolAlignment = Alignment; 0
1460 ----
1461 // Check to see if we already have this constant. ----
1462 // ----
1463 // FIXME, this could be made much more efficient for large constant pools. ----
1464 for (unsigned i = 0, e = Constants.size(); i != e; ++i) 0
1465 if (!Constants[i].isMachineConstantPoolEntry() && 0
1466 CanShareConstantPoolEntry(Constants[i].Val.ConstVal, C, DL)) { 0
1467 if (Constants[i].getAlign() < Alignment) 0
1468 Constants[i].Alignment = Alignment; 0
1469 return i; 0
1470 } ----
1471 ----
1472 Constants.push_back(MachineConstantPoolEntry(C, Alignment)); 0
1473 return Constants.size()-1; 0
1474 } ----

1478 if (Alignment > PoolAlignment) PoolAlignment = Alignment; 0

1481 // ----
1482 // FIXME, this could be made much more efficient for large constant pools. ----
1483 int Idx = V->getExistingMachineCPValue(this, Alignment); 0
1484 if (Idx != -1) { 0
1485 MachineCPVsSharingEntries.insert(V); 0
1486 return (unsigned)Idx; 0

1489 Constants.push_back(MachineConstantPoolEntry(V, Alignment)); 0

1405 static bool CanShareConstantPoolEntry(const Constant *A, const Constant *B, 1405 static bool CanShareConstantPoolEntry(const Constant *A, const Constant *B,
1406 const DataLayout &DL) { 1406 const DataLayout &DL) {
1407 // Handle the trivial case quickly. 1407 // Handle the trivial case quickly.
1408 if (A == B) return true; 1408 if (A == B) return true;

1416 isa(B->getType()) || isa(B->getType())) 1416 isa(B->getType()) || isa(B->getType()))

1422 return false; 1422 return false;

1427 1427
1428 // Try constant folding a bitcast of both instructions to an integer. If we 1428 // Try constant folding a bitcast of both instructions to an integer. If we
1429 // get two identical ConstantInt's, then we are good to share them. We use 1429 // get two identical ConstantInt's, then we are good to share them. We use

1447 1447
1448 // Constants only safely match if A doesn't contain undef/poison. 1448 // Constants only safely match if A doesn't contain undef/poison.
